Having created a basic prototype, it seems we can implement http2 functionality directly in the http adapter by implementing a small custom transport that mimics the interface of the http1.1 transport. In this case, there would be almost no need to modify the existing code, and all functionality except proxies and redirects would work out of the box. Switching the protocol version seems logical by specifying the `httpVersion` option. So far, I don't see any significant downsides to this approach, but at least we won't have to duplicate code when porting.

```js
  try {
    const form = new FormData();

    form.append('foo', '123');

    const {data, headers, status} = await axios.post('https://localhost:8080', form, {
      httpVersion: 2,
      onUploadProgress(e) {
        console.log('upload progress', e);
      },
      onDownloadProgress(e) {
        console.log('download progress', e);
      },
      responseType: 'arraybuffer'
    });


    console.log(data);
    console.log(headers.toJSON());
    console.log(status);
  } catch (err) {
    console.warn(`Error:`, err);
  }
```

