Hey Jarred, we're just following up this case for React Native (https://github.com/facebook/react-native/issues/38025) — which doesn't resolve `"node"` but also doesn't resolve `"browser"` unless targeting web.

I reckon a good solution to this problem is for Axios to invert its conditional export setup to match `"node"`, and ship the browser-compatible export as `"default"`. This matches as wide a set of environments as possible:

- `"node"` means all JS environments with the additional APIs provided by Node.js (**e.g. Bun**).
- `"default"` means other, generally browser-like, JS environments (**e.g. React Native/Hermes**) where utils need to be included as there's no Node standard library.

```js
  "exports": {
    ".": {
      "types": {
        "require": "./index.d.cts",
        "default": "./index.d.ts"
      },
      "node": {
        "require": "./dist/node/axios.cjs",
        "default": "./index.js"
      },
      "default": {
        "require": "./dist/browser/axios.cjs",
        "default": "./index.js"
      }
    },
    ...
  },
```

Bun also resolves the `"node"` condition — at higher priority than `"browser"`, so this would be mutually beneficial, and simpler overall.

