if you're on Node or Workers locally, you should be able to do:
```
npm install axios@github:sgammon/axios
```

Deno, Browser, and so on can just use the examples in the PR summary. Installed this way with `npm`, it will automatically stay up to date with this PR.

on the edge runtime, make sure to follow the `workers` example, i.e. import Axios with:
```js
import axios from "axios/generic";
```

for a quick live example, that worker code actually serves this URL:

https://axios.elide.dev/axios/1.2.1-fetch-beta5/generic/axios.min.mjs

the served URL is, itself, compressed (i.e. the _response_), which you can tell via `Content-Encoding: br`, even though the data in the response was requested with `Accept-Encoding: identity` via Axios.

@reslea take a look at [this example](https://github.com/sgammon/axios/tree/feat/fetch-adapter/examples/fetch#passing-options-to-the-fetch-adapter); the option you pass to Axios is called `fetchOptions`. the options you can pass to fetch vary by platform.

the typings for Axios won't declare the next properties you are looking for (if you are in TypeScript), but there is nothing stopping you from passing whatever options you want.

```js
axios('https://...', {
  adapter: 'fetch',
  fetchOptions: {
    credentials: 'include',
    mode: 'cors',
  },
});
```

i believe the options are passed directly, literally, to the underlying fetch implementation, to facilitate custom options like your case with next.

@arnthors the problem at the moment is that the maintainers have not been very active in this PR. you can see where I have requested builds, PR reviews, and so on.

the fork is usable with its own script. you can find [samples for how to use it here](https://github.com/sgammon/axios/tree/feat/fetch-adapter/examples/fetch).

i would be happy to release this fork as a different (add-on) library, but I worry that it would best be integrated in Axios itself.

