@chinesedfan Yes, the [`cp-axios`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/cp-axios) wrapper extends the cancellation API and indirectly fixes the leakage, since it uses one short-lived cancel token per request, but memory leakage is a serious design flaw for the Axios core that causes RAM overhead. Fixing the core with a wrapper is a dubious approach. This is definitely not what the developers expect when they use such a popular library.  According to StackOverflow, some people use one cancel token for a batch of requests or even define token globally for some functionality. IMHO the best solution- temporary fix cancelToken to keep existing API for a while and add support for AbortController (#3305 ), well-known to frontend developers. AbortController has a method to unsubscribe, original cancelToken doesn't. This can cause leakage, depending on how long the token var lives. In addition, using an existing well-known API improves user experience.
This PR only adds the cancel method on the returned promise, so this is just a shortcut if we want to cancel a single request- I believe it's much easier than defining the cancel source & token somewhere. This PR can be ignored, but the second (#3305  ) might fix the core a bit.

```javascript
const source = axios.CancelToken.source();
// Pseudo code
(async()=>{
    for(let i=0; i<1000; i++){
        await (function request(token){
            token.then(()=> this.abort()); // axios does this internally
            //make a request here
            this.on('done', ()=>{
                // we should to unsubscribe from the token here, but we cannot do that with cancelToken API
            })
        })(source.token);
    }

    //here we got a token.promise with 1000 appended `then` chains/callbacks, requests can not be garbaged normally;
})();

```

