@nickuraltsev So, after all it's not as simple as giving anything we have to `deepMerge`. The rules have to be more specific. Dealing with falsy values especially.

Why? Because if e.g. request-specific options contain `{ proxy: false }`, it should override anything in the defaults. `deepMerge({ ... }, false)` would just return another object with the defaults still in.

Here's a commented version of the rules. Please let me know if you can see any potential for simplifying this, but I honestly can't:

```js
if (utils.isObject(config2[prop])) {
  // config1 property is an object, always merge
  // E.g. { proxy: { host: '', ... } }
  config[prop] = utils.deepMerge(config1[prop], config2[prop]);
} else if (typeof config2[prop] !== 'undefined') {
  // config1 property is present, it overrides config2
  // E.g. { proxy: false }
  config[prop] = config2[prop];
} else if (utils.isObject(config1[prop])) {
  // config1 property is not present and config2 property is an object, which must be dereferenced
  config[prop] = utils.deepMerge(config1[prop]);
} else if (typeof config1[prop] !== 'undefined') {
  // Finally, if there's config1 property, use it
  config[prop] = config1[prop];
}
```

PS. JavaScript is great! `typeof null === 'object'`

---

