We're using [sinon](https://www.npmjs.com/package/sinon) and [sinon-as-promised](https://www.npmjs.com/package/sinon-as-promised) for creating stubs in our tests. Stubbing the `axios.get` method looks something like this:

``` js
const axios = require('axios')
const sinon = require('sinon')
require('sinon-as-promised')

...

beforeEach(() => {
  const mockApiResponse = { id: 'asdf' }
  sinon.stub(axios, 'get').resolves({ data: mockApiResponse })
})

afterEach(() => {
  axios.get.restore()
}
```

It is not possible to mock out the root `axios` function with sinon. The only way to mock a function that is exported as the root of `module.exports` is to mock the module loading system using something like [mock-require](https://www.npmjs.com/package/mock-require) or [proxyquire](https://www.npmjs.com/package/proxyquire). Mocking the module loading system is more heavy handed and takes more setup, so I prefer not to go that route.

If `axios.request` was available, then I could simply `sinon.stub(axios, 'request').resolves({ data: mockApiResponse })` and my test would be ready to go.

